The base-level average values of the rates for India are tabulated in Table 2. As we have argued that at the start of the pandemic, the incubation period is almost zero as the most number of population start at the infected compartment. In time, however, the incubation period will be applied to all the exposed population, who are being monitored. In the same way, in the beginning, the infection through the asymptomatic population would be very small unless there is a large scale of migration of people. This always happens, but not at the beginning. Again, if we consider the effect of the nationwide lockdown, which most countries have resorted to, we can safely assume that the disease transmission rate constantly decreases, eventually becoming zero as people become accustomed to social distancing norms.Table 2
